   "snippet": "A 19 year old woman is brought in 4 hours after ingesting an unknown quantity of aspirin. She is tachypneic and reports tinnitus. Arterial blood gas on room air: pH 7.44, PaCO2 18 mmHg, HCO3 12 mEq/L. Serum electrolytes: Na+ 140, Cl 101, HC",
   "text": "Nephrology Acid-Base (Mixed Disorder) acid-base salicylate anion-gap respiratory-alkalosis Winters USMLE-style / MedKOS (Winter's formula; salicylate toxicology) A 19 year old woman is brought in 4 hours after ingesting an unknown quantity of aspirin. She is tachypneic and reports tinnitus. Arterial blood gas on room air: pH 7.44, PaCO2 18 mmHg, HCO3 12 mEq/L. Serum electrolytes: Na+ 140, Cl 101, HCO3 12 (anion gap 27). Which of the following best characterizes her acid base disorder? A. Acute respiratory alkalosis alone B. High anion gap metabolic acidosis with appropriate respiratory compensation C. Mixed high anion gap metabolic acidosis and primary respiratory alkalosis D. High anion gap metabolic acidosis with a superimposed metabolic alkalosis E. Primary respiratory acidosis AG 27의 고음이온차 대사성 산증이 있으나, Winter 공식으로 예측한 보상 PaCO2(1.5×12+8=26±2)보다 실제 PaCO2(18)가 더 낮다. 즉 보상 범위를 넘는 별도의 원발성 호흡성 알칼리증이 공존한다 — salicylate 중독의 전형적 혼합장애."
